segments.text: A couple of things which occurred while you were a student that had been of some interest to us and wondered what you might be able to tell us about it, which I guess was your freshman year.
There were two incidents of some interest.
One was the incident involving the rice owl.
Yeah.
And the other, the branding of Bevo.
Do you have any recollection of those two?
No, I have a very...

strong recollection of the Rice Owl episode, not that I was involved in it, but one of the football players who roomed right across the hall from me when I was a freshman was wakened, and these boys from Rice came up and, well, we had stolen the owl down there and brought it up here, and they
I believe there were two cars up.
I remember I mentioned maybe just one car.
And they drove up here and got the owl.
And could have gotten away, but in their exuberance before they left the campus, they hollered and woke everybody up.
So the posse formed.
There was a train that came through here at, oh, 4.30 or something like that in the morning.
And they rushed down there, 15 or 20 of them, and got on that train and went to Navasota.
and blocked the road, which in those days wasn't too hard, just a dirt road, and captured them and brought them back up here.
And I can remember at noon the next day on the steps of Speza Hall, Dr. Brazell and the leaders in this posse were there on the steps, and they had these rice boys.
They were all, I don't remember, were they handcuffed or whatnot?
Anyhow, they had them captured.
They had, among them was a, I believe, a private detective from Houston.
They had probably hired to help them.
And they let all the boys go the next day, I think, but this private detective, he kept for a week.
The room wouldn't let him out.
The branding of Bevo, I didn't know a thing about.
I was just
I knew about the incident.
They were all upperclassmen, and there were pictures in the paper about it.
Back to the Rice Owl incident.
What did they do to this detective that they kept confined?
I don't remember anything he did except just kept him in a room locked up.
But then presumably finally let him go.
Oh, yeah, they let him go.
There again, I think the spirit of that kind of thing in those days was a little more carefree.
Nobody was mad at anybody.
Nobody got hurt.
I think the university people, when they branded the steer, they applauded.
They thought that was a pretty good trick.
One thing in connection with the branding of Bevo that we've been trying to track down, we have a couple of pictures of the steer with the 13 to 0 brand on it.
In view of your leadership position among the student body during your senior year, I want to ask you this.
One of those pictures has a clipping on the back of it
Well, one of the pictures, and we also have an invitation to a banquet, which we feel occurred in January of 1920, which would have been your senior year.
Indications are that this steer was slaughtered, and they had a banquet in Austin, to which people from the athletic department at A&M and the administration at A&M were invited.
And the meal was Bevo.
Yeah.
Do you have any recollection of that?
Oh, I don't.
I sure don't.
And one of the articles that's pasted to the back of one of the pictures indicates that the hide of the animal was skinned, I mean was cured, and each school got a half of it.
I don't know.
You don't have any?
I don't have any recollection of that.
Uh-huh.

Well, I was wondering in view of the fact that, you know, your position on campus and then your position with the Association of Former Students, we can't find any other evidence that A&M ever had half the height of Bevo.
I don't remember anything about it.
I sure don't.
The other, one other thing involving Bevo was that, you know, the story has long been told that this 13 to 0 brand was changed to read Bevo.
and that this is how the animal got its name.
Well, I don't know.
I never had heard that.
I would doubt it.
I don't know.
I think the steer's name was Beevil when they branded it, wasn't it?
Well, this is one thing we have never really been able to figure out.
There is some...
indication somewhere that we picked up that the animal's name was Bevo before the branding.
That's what I thought.
Some people have indicated that they thought that the 13-0 was converted to 13 to a B and the dash into an E and a V was stuck in and the zero became the O of Bevo.
We've been told Bevo was a rather popular non-alcoholic drink that was served on campus.
An imitation beer.
Now, was Bevo sold in College Station or brand also?
I don't know.
I imagine it was.
I don't know whether it was just a general term for all imitation beer or not.
Or whether it was a particular brand that might have been popular in Austin.
Yeah, I don't know.
I hadn't thought about it.
Well, it's one of those things that we still need to do some work on, I think.
But we've been asking about as many people as we can find who are around at that point to see what they may know about it.
Let's see, I believe you played basketball for all four years that you were here.
Well, yeah, four years.
You played freshman basketball and three years of varsity.
And then you were captain of the championship team in 1920.
What was collegiate basketball like in the teens and 20s?
Oh, it was more a wrestling match.
It wasn't anything like today's games.
Of course, the players today are so much more skillful and so much bigger.
We had a boy on our team, Tiny Keene, who was about six feet four, and he was a curiosity around the league.
I mean, we called him the Giant.
Nobody had ever seen a basketball player that tall before.
He wasn't too good, but...
It wasn't until later years that these giants started coming along.
And, of course, they changed the game up.
But I would guess from what you said, being more of a wrestling match than anything, than today's game, that there was less calling of fouls.
Oh, yeah.
I believe all four years I played, you designated one foul shooter.
He shot all the fouls for your team.
Of course, you always picked out the one that could shoot them the best.
Uh-huh.
And my recollection is he might go try six or seven, eight, or ten fouls a game.
That'd be about all of those.
Nowadays, 50, 60.
50 in the game.
Yeah.
And that's about more than one a minute in the game.
Yeah.
Yeah.
So someone has told us that the man who had the ball was kind of fair game.
He was fair game.
Everybody was after him.
He could do almost anything within reason to get the ball.
He couldn't grab hold of them, but as far as blocking away the elbows and knees and hips, well, that was all right.
He could do that.
And I believe you ran track, I believe, as a freshman.
I tried to run track, but I wasn't very successful.
What was your specialty in that?
Half mile.
Half mile.
Yeah.
And let's see.
I believe in your senior year, you were a second lieutenant in the Ross Volunteers.
Could you tell us a little bit about that organization
How did you become a member of the RV, and then how were the officers chosen?
Well, it was pretty much a social organization.
Well, practically altogether a social organization, and you had to be elected to membership by the organization.
I don't think we did any drilling.
I don't remember any drilling.
I think we had RV uniforms all right.
I guess we could stand up in a line.
but as far as appearing at public affairs, I don't remember any at all.
We had a big R.B.
dance every spring, which was one of the big college dances, and I think we wore our uniforms then, but as far as appearing at governors and inaugurals,
Mardi Gras, things of that sort.
But was it still billed as a crack drill team?
No, I don't think so.
It seems to me earlier when they first started that they... Well, I expect earlier days they did.
Then it kind of went down, I guess.
And finally, the military department pretty well took it over, which they have now, just my understanding of it.
And it's no longer...
But it was sort of, it operated like a fraternity in those earlier days, let's say.
If you weren't well liked, you didn't get elected to the RVs.
No matter how good you were at drilling.
And then were the officers,
Say you were a second lieutenant.
Was that an appointment by somebody else?
I think it was elected.
I think it was elected officers.
Well, that's somewhat maybe of a carryover of the earlier military tradition, and I know almost all of the companies organized in the Civil War elected their own officers.
It was more like a fraternity than anything else, I guess, as far as...
election was concerned and the membership was concerned.
Membership was highly regarded, but I think more as a social recognition than anything else.
Your senior Longhorn indicated you were also a member of the Junto Society.
Could you tell us a little bit about that organization?
Well, that was Tommy Mayo was responsible for that, I think.
And it was just a group of students and a few faculty members who were interested in discussions of one kind or another.
And I was one of the original members.
We pondered a long time on a name, and finally, I believe Tommy May will come up with Junto, which I think he said in Spanish means a gathering.
And we would meet sometimes at these professors' houses, sometimes in a room somewhere, and each member had to deliver a paper every year, sometime during the year, and he could select his topics.
So it would have been a pretty limited membership then.
Oh, I'd say a dozen maybe at most.
In order to get around to everybody in a reasonable number of meetings.
Yeah, but that was Mayo and we had a man in the English department named Thomas, Bill Thomas, who was also involved in it.
Miss Thomas used to be in the library for a long time after he died.
And we had a character in the architecture department named Gilbert Geist, who was instrumental in it.
It was just a nice, it was a nice activity as far as, for people who were interested in that kind of thing.
So then did you have a, someone each meeting gave a paper and then did you discuss the paper or?
Yeah, yeah.
Discussed the topic.
Mm-hmm.
So almost everybody had to do a little preparation.
Everybody had to do some work.
You knew in advance what the subject of the paper was to be, I take it.
I think so, yeah.
And let's see, I believe you were also associate editor to the battalion.
That didn't mean anything.
It didn't mean anything.
It didn't mean anything.
I don't remember work.
I just don't remember what I did or anything on the battalion.
Well, generally the associate's supposed to help the editor.
That's right.
But I guess if an editor works it right, he passes all the work on to somebody else.
He's a good executive.
And if he does that, then the associate really doesn't have that much to do.
Okay.
How is it that you happen to pick animal husbandry as a
made your field.
I don't know, to tell you the truth.
I had no agricultural background.
Your father was a railroad man.
That's right.
I worked on a farm one summer, but I guess it's sort of romantic, you know, cowboy life, one thing or another.
Why I did, I don't really know.
Probably you didn't have that field chosen before you came here, I would imagine.
Well, I guess I did.
I knew what I was going to take.
As I say, I probably took it because I didn't have to have any math.
Uh-huh.
Animal husbandry.
I was wondering whether maybe after you'd been here a year or two, you encountered a faculty member in that department.
You mentioned John Burns, I guess, was head of the department.
No, I never did.
I don't recall any doubts about changing.
I couldn't have changed to engineering.
I couldn't do engineering.
I couldn't do math.
And, uh,
Of course, that was pretty much all they had in those days, in agriculture and engineering.
Well, then you mentioned sometime during the spring of your senior year, Dr. Mayo suggested perhaps you go to... Mizzell.
Mizzell, I mean.
Mizzell suggested that you get a master's and then come back here and teach, which you did for one year.
And you did teach animal husbandry at that point.
Yeah.
And then you went to Dallas, I believe you said, and you were in the insurance business.
What type of insurance business were you in?
Life insurance.
Life insurance.
Hated every minute of it.
Well, I've been told by a life insurance agent at one point that trying to sell life insurance in the days before Social Security was really kind of a losing proposition.
Nobody wanted it.
I just didn't like it at all.
I made a living in it.
I was delighted to come back here.
You say you were delighted to come back.
Was the offer made to you?
Yeah.
Someone from here approached you to come back into the- Well, I knew Colonel Ashburn from my days in school.
What was his position in the university or in the college?
Well, when he first came down here, he was a publicity officer for the college.
Information officer, we call him now.
Then I believe he moved from that into Secretary of the Former Student Association.
Uh-huh.
Somewhere along the line, he was Commandant at one point, I believe.
I guess he was Commandant before he went at the Former Student Association.
Yeah.
And then you came here in... Fall of 25.
Fall of 25 as an assistant to Ashburn.
Yeah.
He left then in the spring of 26.
I succeeded him.
What were your...
principal duties as an assistant to him?
Well, I helped edit the Texas Aggie, which in those days was a newspaper.
Yeah.
And did anything else.
Of course, the program was much smaller in those days than it is now.
Not nearly as many alumni.
He did the traveling.
I didn't do much traveling.
He went on, he transferred then, I believe, to the information office.
Seems somewhere, I believe, I indicated.
I'm not sure about the sequence there.
He came, he was information officer.
Oh, okay.
Well, maybe I'm thinking something else.
Then the war came along, and he was a highly decorated hero in the war.
And then I believe he was commandant.
And then he was former student secretary.
He left here.
His wife died then.
And he left here to go to Houston, I believe, as head of the Chamber of Commerce.
Oh, okay.
And I believe somewhere I picked up that you taught in the history department for a couple years.
Oh, one year.
I was just, I was moonlighting.
You were?
I guess that was the year I came down here.
The first year you were with the Association of Former Students.
What courses did you teach?
Medieval Europe.
Medieval history.
Had you had any courses in that?
Yes, I had.
I always liked history.
I liked teaching history.
But that was something you filled in.
I filled in.
And then I do have one
teaching distinction, I taught the first course in genetics offered here.
Was that when you first?
That was that year I came back here.
I had had a course in genetics.
I never had heard of genetics.
I had a course in genetics at Wisconsin.
And Dean Kyle called me up one day and said, didn't you have a course in genetics at Wisconsin?
I said, yeah.
He said, you're going to teach a course next term.
OK. Then in 27, I believe it was, you became executive director of the Association of Former Students following that.
26, I believe.
26, yeah.
What size of an operation was that at that point?
I mean, you were an executive director.
How many people did you have working under you?
Well, I had one man and one girl, I think.
Just one, I believe.
Then we just gradually grew.
We never did have over five when I was five or six.
We didn't have much money nowadays.
They got plenty of money.
They're just doing fine over there.
Well, I don't think they'll ever admit that they have plenty.
Well, no, I'm sure of that.
They have substantial sums, anyway.
I read a newspaper clipping that was in your biographical file, and they mentioned a number of things that were inaugurated while you were
uh, executive secretary.
And I thought I might talk with you about those a little bit, see what you have, uh, your recollections are about them.
One of the things, uh, that was done while you were executive secretary was the organization of the placement office.
Yeah.
Can you tell us a little bit about the background as to how that came into being?
And I mean, I take it there was no placement service.
There was no placement services.
I don't, uh,

I just remember promoting the idea and I think we financed, the former students financed the first year of it and I hired the first director and later along the line the college took it over and became quite a good size office.
I believe ultimately they kind of developed two placement offices, one in education and one for everybody else.
Yeah, that's the latest development.
Well, I believe they're merging those.
Are they?
I believe next year they're supposed to be all under one.
All under one, yeah.
I believe they had a placement office in teacher placement.
They've had the two, and I believe now that's all going to be in one.
Well, through the years, and particularly in those days...
The former students were always ahead of the college in their thinking and dreaming.
We had a succession of presidents who were not particularly interested in branching out on that thing.
And we were always promoting them to do something, like the placement office.
I think we promoted that.
And we promoted the archives office.
I don't remember.
I believe we financed that.
I believe the former students financed that for a year or two.
Yeah, I believe for maybe as much as three, at least in part.
And then the university put up some money.
And I believe the former students, let's see, financed the first three years pretty heavily.
And then the fourth year, another amount.
And I've not been able to track down what's come since then.
Well, I don't remember either.
I remember we were always proposing items, and it was Grassley who got them over.
And I guess I would have to say, in addition to proposing items, you were kind of putting your money where your mouth was, too.
Well, you had to get them started.
You had to get them started financially as well as idea-wise.
And the university, the school finally took them over then.
I know that
That said, before the placement office was organized, I know that recruiters came to the campus to interview people.
Who did they get in touch with?
I guess they just went to the department head, as far as I know.
The placement office then would simplify matters.
Simplify matters, give them a place to start from.
And would also give the students a place to go to.
I believe you also were involved in starting the annual giving program that ultimately developed into the development fund.
How had you solicited money prior to that?
We had dues, $5 a year dues.
There is a national organization of alumni secretaries, and I started going to their meetings.
I got a lot of big ideas.
And I discovered that these schools that have an annual giving fund were just taking in a whole lot more money than we were.
And so I got the idea, and we just gradually promoted.
There again, it was our promotion.
And we held joint meetings with the board of directors of the college in one thing or another, and had to work out some financial arrangements.
And the college helped us a little financially for a number of years.
And that's the way it came about.
So then what you did was substitute an annual giving program for dues.
your dues were, what, $5 a year?
$5 a year.
And this was used primarily to support the office of the... Support the office, yeah.
Of the secretary, executive secretary and the staff.
All the support they had.
And so you really didn't have, at that point, you didn't have any money that you could really kind of turn over to the college.
No, we didn't have any money at all.
We were doing well to keep our heads above water.
Where did you have offices at that point?
Uh...
Well, let's see.
When I came down here, we had officers in the Civil Engineering Building.
Then we had a fire, and we had officers in the basement of the M.E.
Building, and then we moved down to the System Administration Building.
I don't remember just where we were when we, where our officers were when we started the development fund.
I would guess probably we were down at the administration building then.
That was early in the 30s, I think, or no, early in the 40s.
Yeah, because that's mid-30s, the systems building, I believe, was mid to late 30s.
Yeah, yeah.
And certainly the former students were deeply involved in the promotion of the Memorial Student Center.
Well, yeah, there again, we had to promote the idea.
It was, it had been
suggested through the years.

Students, one thing or another, one class way back there had put their class, these classes usually end up the year with a few hundred dollars, and they had designated that as the beginning of a student union fund, and the former students held it.
And so we started promoting it, and made that
I guess the first objective of the annual giving, which was a natural.
And we got, I think, $250,000, and then, of course, the college put the rest of the money up.
But it was largely a case of moving the board of directors, you know, get them to take a step.
People were pretty scared in those days, much more than they are now.
They were scared of what people were saying.
I used to argue about having Sunday picture shows when I was over at the air-dome.
We'd have Sunday picture shows.
I was afraid of what people would say.
Of course, they probably would have said plenty of it.
Yeah, I can remember.
But that's pretty much past.
I don't think, oh, you have to keep it in your mind.
You can't go out and do violence to public opinion, but it's far less than it was.
But the $250,000 which the association contributed towards the MSC, can you recall about how long it took you to accumulate that amount?
I believe three years.
I believe we had a three year objective.
